## Step 3 — Add the Right Index

### B-tree (default — for equality and range)
```sql
-- Single column (user_id equality)
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY orders_user_id_idx ON orders(user_id);

-- Composite (user_id + status — covers WHERE user_id = x AND status = y)
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY orders_user_status_idx ON orders(user_id, status);

-- Partial index (only index a subset — much smaller, faster)
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY active_orders_idx ON orders(user_id)
WHERE status IN ('pending', 'processing') AND deleted_at IS NULL;
```

### GIN index (for JSONB, arrays, full-text search)
```sql
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY products_tags_idx ON products USING gin(tags);
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY events_metadata_idx ON events USING gin(metadata);
-- For full-text search:
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY posts_fts_idx ON posts USING gin(fts);
```

### BRIN index (for time-series / append-only tables)
```sql
-- Very small index, works well for timestamps on large tables
-- Only useful if rows are inserted in time order (most event tables are)
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY events_created_at_brin ON events USING brin(created_at);
```

### CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY — always use this in production
```sql
-- Regular CREATE INDEX locks the table for writes (dangerous in production)
-- CONCURRENTLY builds in background — table stays writable — takes longer
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY my_new_index ON orders(user_id, created_at);
-- Takes longer (2-3x) but never causes downtime
```

### When NOT to add an index
- Columns with very low cardinality (boolean, 2-3 possible values)
- Tables under 1,000 rows (sequential scan is faster)
- Write-heavy columns (every INSERT/UPDATE must update every index)
- Already have a composite index that covers this column as the first element

