## RLS Performance

RLS policies run on every row — they must be fast. Slow policies degrade every query.

### Common RLS performance issues

**Problem: calling auth.uid() per row**
```sql
-- SLOW — auth.uid() called once per row evaluated
CREATE POLICY "slow" ON orders FOR SELECT USING (user_id = auth.uid());

-- FAST — auth.uid() called once, result reused
CREATE POLICY "fast" ON orders FOR SELECT USING (
  user_id = (SELECT auth.uid())
);
```

**Problem: function call in policy without STABLE/IMMUTABLE**
```sql
-- SLOW — function re-evaluated for every row
CREATE POLICY "slow" ON orders USING (get_user_role() = 'admin');

-- FAST — mark function as STABLE so result is cached within query
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION get_user_role()
RETURNS TEXT LANGUAGE sql STABLE AS $$
  SELECT role FROM user_roles WHERE user_id = auth.uid();
$$;
```

**Problem: policy without supporting index**
```sql
-- Every RLS policy filter needs an index on the filtered column
-- If you have: USING (user_id = auth.uid())
-- You MUST have: CREATE INDEX ON table(user_id);
-- Without it — Seq Scan on every authenticated query
```

### Verify RLS is not the bottleneck
```sql
-- Temporarily disable RLS and run EXPLAIN — if suddenly fast, RLS is the issue
SET row_security = off;
EXPLAIN ANALYZE SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id = 'abc';
SET row_security = on;
```

---

## The 3 Bottleneck Types

| Bottleneck | Symptom | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Missing index (I/O) | Seq Scan on large table, high "Rows Removed by Filter" | Add composite index on filtered columns |
| Too many connections (CPU/memory) | pg_stat_activity shows many idle connections | Switch to port 6543, set `max: 1` in serverless clients |
| RLS function overhead (CPU) | Query fast without RLS, slow with | Add `(SELECT auth.uid())` wrapper, mark functions STABLE |

